{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5fb4bd8d-4b98-42e9-97cb-8bcd9663f414","content":"**Use `dotnet workload update`.**\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After a SDK update, this is what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads *at their current versions*. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but does **not** upgrade them. If your workloads are simply outdated relative to the new SDK, this won't help.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you also want to verify which workloads are installed, run `dotnet workload list` first.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2e12c22b-d1f8-4636-acb1-25a55b7311e6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":244,"requestId":"D446:29787D:1CD68CC:20671C8:6A07C13A"},"id":"fd53ee91-5efb-48ef-bb58-7fa6fcf69ef7","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:58:41.281Z","parentId":"08854869-2ca1-47eb-a1f8-ecbc94a8c7cf"}
